INSERT INTO section_text (section_id, language, text)
VALUES
(
  (SELECT section_id FROM sections WHERE section_number = 'H 4908'),
  'en',
  'AN ACT relating to the establishment of the Texas prosperity payout fund; imposing taxes on the gross revenues of and consumption by certain industry participants; authorizing administrative penalties.

SECTION 1. This Act may be cited as the Texas Prosperity Payout Act.

SECTION 2. Chapter 403, Government Code, is amended by adding Subchapter V to read as follows:

SUBCHAPTER V. TEXAS PROSPERITY PAYOUT FUND

Sec. 403.701. FINDINGS AND PURPOSE. The legislature finds that emerging industries, including artificial intelligence and cryptocurrency mining, significantly impact this state''s energy, infrastructure, and workforce resources; that revenue generated by these industries has not been proportionately invested in the prosperity of the residents of this state; and that a permanent fund dividend can promote economic stability, foster community resilience, and stimulate local economies. The purpose of this subchapter is to establish a permanent fund dividend benefiting adult Texans through a revenue-supported structure that complies with Section 51, Article III, Texas Constitution, ensures fiscal sustainability and transparency, and adheres to all applicable constitutional provisions regarding the permissible uses of public funds.

Sec. 403.702. DEFINITIONS. "Prosperity payout" means a payment made from the Texas prosperity payout fund. "Eligible resident" means an individual who is a United States citizen or lawful permanent resident, is at least 18 years of age, and has resided in Texas for at least 12 consecutive months verified through government-issued identification or applicable state records. "Fund" means the Texas prosperity payout fund created under this subchapter.

Sec. 403.703. TEXAS PROSPERITY PAYOUT FUND. The Texas prosperity payout fund is created as a fund outside the state treasury with the comptroller. The fund consists of money transferred or deposited by the constitution, general law, or the General Appropriations Act; revenue dedicated by the legislature for deposit to the fund; and gifts, grants, and donations. The comptroller shall administer the fund and distribute prosperity payouts to eligible residents. Money deposited to the fund is automatically appropriated to the comptroller for making prosperity payouts without further legislative appropriation.

Sec. 403.704. PROSPERITY PAYOUT. The comptroller shall issue a monthly prosperity payout to each verified eligible resident. The payout amount equals the total money in the fund on the last day of the preceding month divided by the number of eligible residents receiving a payout that month. The comptroller shall adopt rules for verifying eligible residents and issuing payouts. Prosperity payouts are considered refunds of collected industry-specific tax revenue to the public, serving the public purposes of promoting economic stability and public prosperity.

Sec. 403.705. TRANSPARENCY AND REPORTING. Not later than December 31 of each state fiscal year, the comptroller shall prepare a report to the lieutenant governor and speaker of the house covering the total tax revenue collected organized by industry, total money disbursed from the fund, and economic impact assessments of each tax and payout issued. The report shall be posted on the comptroller''s website. Economic impact assessments must be conducted by an independent third party using generally accepted economic forecasting models, including baseline comparisons and anticipated long-term effects on different population segments.

Sec. 403.706. OVERSIGHT AND AUDITING. The state auditor shall conduct a quarterly audit of the fund to ensure its integrity. An independent oversight committee of at least seven members appointed by the governor shall annually review economic impact data. Members must include representatives from the Legislative Budget Board and the state auditor''s office and at least three public members. Committee members must opt out of receiving prosperity payouts and may not have a direct financial interest in any entity subject to a tax under Chapter 210, Tax Code.

Sec. 403.707. AUTOMATIC ENROLLMENT AND OPT OUT. An eligible recipient is automatically enrolled with the comptroller to receive prosperity payouts effective on the first day of the month following the month in which eligibility is first met. An eligible recipient may opt out at any time through procedures established by the comptroller and may opt back in at any time without penalty or delay other than standard processing times.

Sec. 403.708. FRAUD PREVENTION AND DISPUTE RESOLUTION; APPEAL. The comptroller shall implement verification protocols to prevent fraudulent claims. An individual determined ineligible may appeal before the State Office of Administrative Hearings within 30 days of the final determination, bearing the burden of proof by a preponderance of the evidence. An appellant facing immediate financial hardship may request expedited review, with a decision issued within 10 business days.

SECTION 3. CHAPTER 210. TAX ON INDUSTRY REVENUE AND CONSUMPTION. Imposes the following taxes: (1) Electricity consumption tax on cryptocurrency mining operations at $0.10 per kilowatt-hour, exempting operations consuming less than 5 MWh/month; (2) 6% gross revenue tax on artificial intelligence infrastructure facilities with annual revenue over $50 million; (3) 4% gross revenue tax on data centers consuming more than 5 MWh/month; (4) 2% gross revenue tax on semiconductor manufacturers; (5) 2% gross revenue tax on cloud service providers with annual data usage exceeding five petabytes; (6) 2% gross revenue tax on telecommunications companies serving 500,000 or more subscribers; (7) 2% gross revenue tax on large software companies generating at least $50 million in annual software revenue. Each taxable person shall file a monthly report with the comptroller on or before the 20th day of the following calendar month and pay the tax due with the report. Failure to submit a required report is subject to an administrative penalty not to exceed $10,000. Knowingly including false information in a report is subject to a penalty not to exceed $100,000. All revenue collected shall be deposited to the Texas prosperity payout fund and may not be used for any purpose other than funding the monthly payments under Section 403.704, Government Code.

SECTIONS 4-6. IMPLEMENTATION AND EFFECTIVE DATE. Not later than January 1, 2026, the comptroller shall adopt rules necessary to implement this Act. No individual is entitled to a payment before July 1, 2026. This Act takes effect September 1, 2025.'
);

INSERT INTO section_text (section_id, language, text)
VALUES
(
  (SELECT section_id FROM sections WHERE section_number = 'A 3719'),
  'en',
  'AN ACT to amend the tax law, in relation to enacting the "robot tax act".

Section 1. This act shall be known and may be cited as the "robot tax act".

Section 2. The tax law is amended by adding a new section 209-A to read as follows:

Section 209-A. Additional tax on using technology to displace workers. For the privilege of exercising its corporate franchise, or of doing business, or of employing capital, or of owning or leasing property in a corporate or organized capacity, or of maintaining an office, or of deriving receipts from activity in this state, there is hereby imposed on every corporation subject to tax under section 209 of this article a tax surcharge equal to the sum of any taxes or fees imposed by the state or any political subdivision thereof computed based on an employee''s wage — including but not limited to state income tax, state unemployment insurance, and local occupational taxes — for an employee''s final year of employment where such employee was displaced due to their position being replaced by technology. For the purposes of this section, "technology" includes but is not limited to machinery, artificial intelligence algorithms, or computer applications.

A corporation is deriving receipts from activity in this state if it has receipts within this state of one million dollars or more in the taxable year. A corporation is doing business in this state if it has issued credit cards to one thousand or more customers with a mailing address in this state, has merchant customer contracts covering one thousand or more locations in this state, or the combined total of such customers and locations equals one thousand or more.

A foreign corporation shall not be deemed to be doing business in this state solely by reason of: maintaining cash balances with banks or trust companies in this state; owning shares of stock or securities kept in a safe deposit box, vault, or deposited with banks or brokers in safekeeping; maintenance of an office in this state by officers or directors who are not employees of the corporation; or the keeping of books or records in this state not kept by employees of the corporation.

An alien corporation shall not be deemed to be doing business in this state if its activities are limited solely to investing or trading in stocks, securities, or commodities for its own account. An alien corporation that has no effectively connected income for the taxable year shall not be subject to tax under this article for that taxable year.

Any receiver, referee, trustee, assignee or other fiduciary, or any officer or agent appointed by any court who conducts the business of any corporation, shall be subject to the tax imposed by this article in the same manner and to the same extent as if the business were conducted by the agents or officers of such corporation. A dissolved corporation which continues to conduct business shall also be subject to the tax imposed by this article.

At the end of each year, the commissioner shall review the cumulative percentage change in the consumer price index (CPI-U) and shall adjust receipt thresholds if the index has changed by ten percent or more since January 1, 2017, or since the date thresholds were last adjusted, rounded to the nearest one thousand dollars.

Section 3. This act shall take effect immediately and shall apply to taxable years starting January 1, 2026. Effective immediately, the addition, amendment, and/or repeal of any rule or regulation necessary for the implementation of this act are authorized to be made and completed on or before such effective date.'
);


