rson engaged in registering to vote or collecting voter registration applications as an employee or agent of the division, supervisor of elections, Department of Highway Safety and Motor Vehicles, or a voter registration agency. (47) (41) "Undervote" means that the elector does not properly designate any choice for an office or ballot question, and the tabulator records no vote for the office or question. (48) (42) "Uniformed services" means the Army, Navy, Air Force, Marine Corps, Space Force, and Coast Guard, the commissioned corps of the Public Health Service, and the commissioned corps of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. (49) "Voter data" means all voter records pertaining to an individual voter, including voter registration, voter signature, voter registration changes, voted status, and voting history. (50) (43) "Voter interface device" means any device that communicates voting instructions and ballot information to a voter and allows the voter to select and vote for candidates and issues. A voter interface device may not be used to tabulate votes. Any vote tabulation must be based upon a subsequent scan of the marked marksense ballot or the voter-verifiable paper output after the voter interface device process has been completed. (51) (44) "Voter registration agency" means any office that provides public assistance, any office that serves persons with disabilities, any center for independent living, or any public library. (52) (45) "Voter registration official" means any supervisor of elections or individual authorized by the Secretary of State to accept voter registration applications and execute updates to the statewide voter registration system. (53) (46) "Voting booth" or "booth" means that booth or enclosure wherein an elector casts his or her ballot for tabulation by an electronic or electromechanical device. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (54) (47) "Voting system" means a method of casting and processing votes that functions wholly or partly by use of electromechanical or electronic apparatus or by use of marksense ballots and includes, but is not limited to, the procedures for casting and processing votes and the programs, operating manuals, supplies, printouts, and other software necessary for the system''s operation. Section 2. Section 101.015, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 101.015 Standards for voting systems, other election systems, and election material security. -- (1) The Department of State shall adopt rules which establish minimum standards for hardware, and software, and security measures for electronic and electromechanical voting systems and other election systems. Such rules must be evaluated annually by the Election Technology Advisory Board and updated annually by the department. The rules must shall contain standards for: (a) Functional requirements; (b) Performance levels; (c) Physical and design characteristics; (d) Documentation requirements; and (e) Evaluation criteria; . (f) Security, auditability, chain of custody, and reporting compliance; (g) Auditable storage methods; (h) Portable data storage requirements; (i) Which data network communications components, sub components, configurations, and settings are specifically allowed or prohibited, as applicable; (j) On-premises deployment requirements; (k) Hardware self-diagnostics, reporting, maintenance plan, and emergency support requirements; (l) Department review and favorable assessment of vendor software development methodology, code, and functionality; and (m) Department review and favorable assessment of vendor information security practices. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (2)(a) All voting and other election systems must comply with state, federal, and commercial standards in addition to evolving technology, cybersecurity, manual process control, pre election certification auditing, and other enterprise risk management standards that are relevant to the criteria set forth in this section. Notwithstanding the relevant standards, all of the following requirements must be met or exceeded: 1. Tabulators may not use internal or external hardware that enables cellular, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, or other wireless data communications. 2. Data network communications must use an Ethernet switch and category 6 Ethernet cables or the current equivalent technology. 3. Voting systems and other elections systems must be based on open source code that is compiled and distributed by the department, or based on proprietary software that is inspected using real-time reporting and auditing. 4. All software development must be conducted in the United States by United States citizens and must use data stored in the United States. 5. Maintenance must be performed by United States citizens who annually satisfy a background screening requirement. 6. Auditable storage methods must ensure that election data is immutable. 7. Portable storage media must be compatible with state approved county elections security plans that specify portable media chain of custody requirements. 8. Use of hosted services is discouraged and may be certified only if all of the following apply: a. The vendor has secure enclaves. b. The vendor is based within the United States. c. Data is stored only in the United States. d. The software is developed by United States citizens who annually satisfy background screening requirements. e. The hosting of services is operated solely by United States citizens who annually satisfy background screening requirements. 9. System pre-election testing must include evaluation of security software and network communication settings. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 10. System precertification mini-audits must include verification that systems settings have not been changed and that unauthorized data network communication or unauthorized system access has not occurred. (b) If there is a conflict between standards, the Election Technology Advisory Board must determine which standard is to be used based on efficacy, relevancy, cost, and election timeline constraints. Systems deployed before July 1, 2025, or adoption of a department rule or the issuance of new or updated standards may continue to be used if security measures are put in place which adequately mitigate noncompliance risks. The security measures must be outlined in the county security plan approved by the department, as required by department rule. The department shall adopt or modify rules to enforce this subsection. (3) A full supply chain analysis must be conducted on legacy and new hardware, firmware, and software to ensure the certified hardware and software are produced and developed in the United States using components that are free from malware, spyware, and hidden communication or connection capabilities. The Election Technology Advisory Board shall make recommendations on the remedy for legacy technologies that do not meet the requirements of this section. (4) Each odd-numbered year the Department of State shall review the rules governing standards and certification of voting systems to determine the adequacy and effectiveness of such rules in assuring that elections are fair and impartial. (5) (3) The Department of State shall adopt rules to achieve and maintain the maximum degree of correctness, impartiality, and efficiency of the procedures of voting, including write-in voting, and of counting, tabulating, and recording votes by voting systems used in this state. (6)(a) (4)(a) The Department of State shall adopt rules establishing minimum security standards for voting systems. The standards must, at a minimum, must address the following: 1. Chain of custody of ballots, including a detailed description of procedures to create a complete written record of the chain of custody of ballots and paper outputs beginning with their receipt from a printer or manufacturer until such time as they are destroyed. 2. Transport of ballots, including a description of the method and equipment used and a detailed list of the names of all individuals involved in such transport. 3. Ballot security, including a requirement that all ballots be kept in a locked room in the supervisor''s office, a facility controlled by the supervisor or county canvassing board, or a public place in which the county canvassing board is canvassing votes until needed for canvassing and returned thereafter. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (b)1. Each supervisor shall establish written procedures to assure accuracy and security in his or her county, including procedures related to early voting pursuant to s. 101.657. Such procedures must shall be reviewed in each odd-numbered year by the department. 2. Each supervisor shall submit any revisions to the security procedures to the department at least 45 days before early voting commences pursuant to s. 101.657 in an election in which they are to take effect. (7)(a) (5)(a) The Department of State shall adopt rules which establish standards for provisional approval of hardware and software for innovative use of electronic and electromechanical voting systems. Such rules must shall contain standards for: 1. Functional requirements; 2. Performance levels; 3. Physical and design characteristics; 4. Documentation requirements; 5. Evaluation criteria; 6. Audit capabilities; and 7. Consideration of prior use of a system. (b) A voting system may shall be provisionally approved for a total of no more than 2 years, and the Department of State has the authority to revoke such approval. Provisional approval of a system may shall not be granted by the Department of State to supersede certification requirements of this section. (c)1. No provisionally approved system may be used in any election, including any municipal election, without the authorization of the Department of State. 2. An application for use of a provisionally approved system must shall be submitted at least 120 days before prior to the intended use by the supervisor of elections or municipal elections official. Such application must shall request authorization for use of the system in a specific election. Each application must shall state the election, the number of precincts, and the number of anticipated voters for which the system is requested for use. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 3. The Department of State shall authorize or deny authorization of the use of the provisionally approved system for the specific election and shall notify the supervisor of elections or municipal elections official in writing of the authorization or denial of authorization, along with the reasons therefor, within 45 days after receipt of the application. (d) A contract for the use of a provisionally approved system for a specific election may be entered into with the approval of the Department of State. No contract for title to a provisionally approved system may be entered into. (e) The use of any provisionally approved system is shall be valid for all purposes. (8) (6) All electronic and electromechanical voting systems purchased on or after January 1, 1990, must meet the minimum standards established under subsection (1). All electronic and electromechanical voting systems in use on or after July 1, 1993, must meet the minimum standards established under subsection (1) or subsection (7) (5). (9) (7) The Division of Elections shall review the voting systems certification standards and ensure that new technologies are available for selection by boards of county commissioners which meet the requirements for voting systems and meet user standards. The Division of Elections shall continuously review the voting systems certification standards to ensure that new technologies are appropriately certified for all elections in a timely manner. The division shall also develop methods to determine the will of the public with respect to voting systems. Section 3. Section 101.017, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 101.017 Bureau of Voting Systems and Other Election Systems Certification. --There is created a Bureau of Voting Systems and Other Election Systems Certification within the Division of Elections of the Department of State which shall provide technical support to the supervisors of elections and which is responsible for voting system and other election technology standards and certification. The positions necessary for the bureau to accomplish its duties must shall be established through the budgetary process and include at least two credentialed cybersecurity experts. All county security plans and rules relating to election security must be reviewed by the Florida Cybersecurity Advisory Council and a state security risk assessment team at least every odd-numbered year. Section 4. Section 101.018, Florida Statutes, is created to read: 101.018 Election Technology Advisory Board. -- (1) There is created under the Executive Office of the Governor, and with the guidance of the state chief information officer, the Secretary of State, and the Florida Cybersecurity Advisory Council, the Election Technology Advisory Board. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (2) The board shall be responsible for all of the following: (a) Making recommendations on election technology and security standards, certification, procurement, and management policies. If multiple federal or commercial standard options exist, the board must make a recommendation of the standard to be followed based on efficacy, relevancy, cost, and election timeline constraints. (b) Assessing the adherence to and effectiveness of such policies and providing reports on the board''s findings and recommendations annually to the Legislature and biannually to the Secretary of State. The report must include a review and assessment of the security plans implemented by the supervisors and procedural and information technology audit reports. (c) Directing and participating in election security risk assessments annually with guidance and participation from the state chief information officer, the Secretary of State, the Florida Cybersecurity Advisory Council, and industry experts. (3)(a) The Governor shall appoint at least five members to the board. (b) The board must be composed of the following members: 1. At least two members with cybersecurity credentials and a minimum of 10 years of cybersecurity experience. 2. At least one member with proven leadership in relevant emerging technologies, such as network communications or artificial intelligence. 3. At least one member with a proven track record of success in planning, implementing, and overseeing technology in one of the following areas: a. The military. b. A commercial enterprise. c. A government enterprise. 4. At least one member with proven leadership as a former supervisor of elections. 5. At least two members from each major political party. (c) All members must be qualified electors in this state. A member may not be a current employee, contractor, grantee, beneficiary, shareholder, or immediate family member of a supervisor of elections, the department, an election industry vendor, the Federal Government, a foreign government, or a foreign country of concern as defined in s. 287.138. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (d) Three members constitute a quorum. (4) In accordance with s. 20.052(8), this section is repealed October 2, 2028, unless reviewed and saved through reenactment by the Legislature. Section 5. Subsection (1) of section 101.293, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 101.293 Competitive sealed bids and proposals required. -- (1) Any purchase of voting equipment or other election systems, the individual or combined retail value of which is in excess of the threshold amount for CATEGORY TWO purchases provided in s. 287.017, by a governing body must shall be by means of competitive sealed bids or competitive sealed proposals from at least two bidders, except under the following conditions: (a) If a majority of the governing body agrees by vote that an emergency situation exists in regard to the purchase of such equipment to the extent that the potential benefits derived from competitive sealed bids or competitive sealed proposals are outweighed by the detrimental effects of a delay in the acquisition of such equipment; or (b) If a majority of the governing body finds that there is but a single source from which suitable equipment may be obtained. If such conditions are found to exist, the chair of the governing body must shall certify to the Division of Elections the situation and conditions requiring an exception to the competitive sealed bidding and competitive sealed proposal requirements of this section. Such certification must shall be maintained on file by the division. Section 6. Section 101.294, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 101.294 Purchase and sale of voting equipment and other election systems. -- (1) The Division of Elections of the Department of State shall adopt uniform rules for the purchase, use, and sale of voting equipment and other election systems in this the state. Such rules must prohibit outsourcing operations or using the same vendor for multiple functions that, when combined, would enable a single vendor to compromise election security or block transparency or auditing. A No governing body may not shall purchase or cause to be purchased any voting equipment or other election systems unless such equipment has been certified for use in this state by the Department of State. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (2) Any governing body contemplating the purchase or sale of voting equipment or other election systems shall notify the Division of Elections of such considerations. The division shall attempt to coordinate the sale of excess or outmoded equipment by one county with purchases of necessary equipment by other counties. (3) The division shall inform the governing bodies of the various counties of the state of the availability of new or used voting equipment or other election systems and of sources available for obtaining such equipment. (4) A vendor of voting equipment or other election systems may not provide an uncertified voting or other election system, voting or other election system component, or voting or other election system upgrade to a local governing body or supervisor of elections in this state. (5) Before or in conjunction with providing a voting or other election system, voting or other election system component, or voting or other election system upgrade, the vendor shall provide the local governing body or supervisor of elections with a sworn certification that the voting or other election system, voting or other election system component, or voting or other election system upgrade being provided has been certified by the Division of Elections. Section 7. Section 101.295, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 101.295 Penalties for violation. -- (1) Any member of a governing body which purchases or sells voting equipment or other election systems in violation of the provisions of ss. 101.292-101.295, which member knowingly votes to purchase or sell voting equipment or other election systems in violation of the provisions of ss. 101.292-101.295, commits a felony of the third is guilty of a misdemeanor of the first degree, punishable as provided by s. 775.082, or s. 775.083, or s. 775.084, and is shall be subject to suspension from office on the grounds of malfeasance. (2) Any vendor, chief executive officer, or vendor representative of voting equipment who provides a voting system, voting system component, or voting system upgrade in violation of this chapter commits a felony of the third degree, punishable as provided in s. 775.082, s. 775.083, or s. 775.084. Section 8. Section 101.34, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 101.34 Custody of voting system and other election systems. --The supervisor of elections shall be the custodian of the voting system and other election systems in the county, and he or she shall appoint deputies necessary to prepare and supervise the voting system and other election systems before prior to and during elections. The compensation for such deputies shall be paid by the supervisor of elections. Section 9. Subsection (1) of section 101.341, Florida Statutes, is amended, and subsection (2) of that section is reenacted, to read: 101.341 Prohibited activities by voting system, other election system, and election material custodians and deputy custodians. -- (1) A No voting system, other election system, or election material custodian or deputy custodian or other employee of the supervisor of elections, which employee''s duties are primarily involved with the preparation, maintenance, or repair of voting equipment or other election systems, may not accept employment or any form of consideration from any person or business entity involved in the purchase, repair, or sale of voting equipment, other election systems, or election materials unless such employment has the prior written approval of the supervisor of elections of the county by which such person is employed. The supervisor of elections and his or her employees may not seek employment, contracts, or other relationships with suppliers of voting systems, other election systems, election material vendors, or election-related service providers on behalf of family members and must advise family members that such employment, contract, or other relationship creates the appearance of a conflict of interest. The supervisor of elections shall notify the Secretary of State immediately upon learning of such conflict. The Secretary of State may remove a supervisor of elections after learning of a conflict, but not after the conflict is resolved or may retain the supervisor with mandatory satisfactory quarterly reviews of the conflict until it is resolved or until the supervisor has left office. The Secretary of State shall promptly report to the public notice of the conflict, disposition of the office, subsequent reviews, and resolution of the conflict. (2) Any person violating the provisions of this section is guilty of a misdemeanor of the first degree, punishable as provided by s. 775.082 or s. 775.083. Such person shall also be subject to immediate discharge from his or her position. Section 10. Section 101.5604, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 101.5604 Adoption of system; procurement of equipment; commercial tabulations. --The board of county commissioners of any county, at any regular meeting or a special meeting called for the purpose, may, upon consultation with the supervisor of elections, adopt, purchase or otherwise procure, and provide for the use of any electronic or electromechanical voting or other election system approved by the Department of State in all or a portion of the election precincts of that county. Thereafter the electronic or electromechanical voting or other election system may be used for voting at all elections for public and party offices and on all measures and for receiving, registering, and counting the votes thereof in such election precincts as the governing body directs. A county may must use an electronic or electromechanical precinct-count tabulation voting system or may count ballots by hand at the precinct level. Section 11. Section 101.5605, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 101.5605 Examination and approval of equipment. -- (1) The Department of State shall publicly examine all makes of electronic or electromechanical voting systems and other election systems submitted to it and determine whether the systems comply with the requirements of s. 101.5606. (2)(a) Any person owning or interested in an electronic or electromechanical voting system or other election system may submit it to the Department of State for examination. The vote counting segment must shall be certified after a satisfactory evaluation testing has been performed according to the standards adopted under s. 101.015(1). This testing must shall include, but is not limited to, testing of all software required for the voting system''s operation; the ballot reader; the rote processor, especially in its logic and memory components; the digital printer; the fail-safe operations; the counting center environmental requirements; and the equipment reliability estimate. For the purpose of assisting in examining the system, the department shall employ or contract for the services of multiple individuals at least one individual who collectively have expertise in the is expert in one or more fields of software design, cybersecurity, data security, data processing, mechanical engineering, and public administration and shall require from each the individual a written report of his or her examination. (b) The person submitting a system for approval or the board of county commissioners of any county seeking approval of a given system shall reimburse the Department of State in an amount equal to the actual costs incurred by the department in examining the system. Such reimbursement must shall be made regardless of whether or not the system is approved by the department. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (c) Neither The Secretary of State or an nor any examiner may not shall have any pecuniary interest in any voting equipment, other election systems, election materials, or election-related service providers. Upon learning of a potential conflict, an examiner must disclose in writing to his or her supervisor all potential conflicts regarding a family member''s relationships to the voting system, other election systems, election materials, or election-related service providers. The examiner must be excluded from all activities related to the entity with which there is a conflict. (d) The Department of State shall approve or disapprove any voting system or other election system submitted to it within 120 days after the date of its initial submission. (3)(a) Before the Department of State approves the electronic or electromechanical voting system or other election system, the person who submitted it for examination must shall provide the department with the name, mailing address, and telephone number of a registered agent, which agent must have and continuously maintain an office in this state. Any change in the name, address, or telephone number of the registered agent must shall promptly be made known to the department. (b) Before entering into a contract for the sale or lease of a voting system or other election system, any of which is approved under this section, to any county, the person entering into such contract shall provide the department with the name, mailing address, and telephone number of a registered agent, which agent must have and continuously maintain an office in this state. Any change in the name, address, or telephone number of the registered agent must shall promptly be made known to the department. (c) The department''s proof of delivery or attempted delivery to the last mailing address of the registered agent on file with the department at the time of delivery or attempted delivery is valid for all notice purposes. (d) Within 30 days after completing the examination and upon approval of any electronic or electromechanical voting system, the Department of State shall make and maintain a report on the system, together with a written or printed description and drawings and photographs clearly identifying the system and the operation thereof. As soon as practicable after such filing, the department shall send a notice of certification and, upon request, a copy of the report to the governing bodies of the respective counties of the state. Any voting system that does not receive the approval of the department may not be adopted for or used at 