s been overvoted or undervoted. (e) (5) It Is capable of correctly counting votes. (f) (6) Allows It permits each voter at a primary election to vote only for the candidates seeking nomination by the political party in which such voter is registered, for any candidate for nonpartisan office, and for any question upon which the voter is entitled to vote. (g) (7) At presidential elections, allows it permits each elector, by one operation, to vote for all presidential electors of a party or for all presidential electors of candidates for President and Vice President with no party affiliation. (h) (8) It Provides a method for write-in voting. (i) (9) It Is capable of accumulating a count of the specific number of ballots tallied for a precinct, accumulating total votes by candidate for each office, and accumulating total votes for and against each question and issue of the ballots tallied for a precinct. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (j) (10) It Is capable of tallying votes from ballots of different political parties from the same precinct, in the case of a primary election. (k) (11) It Is capable of automatically producing precinct totals in printed form. (l) (12) If it is of a type which registers votes electronically, allows it will permit each voter to change his or her vote for any candidate or upon any question appearing on the official ballot up to the time that the voter takes the final step to register his or her vote and to have the vote computed. (m) (13) It Is capable of providing records from which the operation of the voting system may be audited. Audit reports must be published and made available for inspection during and after an election to the supervisor of elections, canvassing boards, and the public. Audits and reports must include the operating system and other third-party applications on the system. (n) (14) It Uses a precinct-count tabulation system. (o) (15) It Does not use an apparatus or device for the piercing of ballots by the voter. (2) Any other election system or election vendor may not be approved by the Department of State unless it is confirmed that it, at a minimum, does all of the following: (a) Protects confidential voter information, including driver license numbers, social security numbers, signatures, and voted status, before an election. (b) Protects all election information that is not made publicly available. (c) Adequately performs the functions for which it was advertised and marketed. (d) Is capable of providing records from which the operation of other election systems may be audited. Audit reports must be published and made available for inspection during and after an election to the supervisor of elections, canvassing boards, and the public. Such reports must be suited for performing manual cross-checks during system operation in order to verify that unauthorized communications capability and use of unauthorized portable media access were not granted. Section 13. Section 101.56065, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 101.56065 Voting system and other election system defects; disclosure; investigations; penalties. -- (1) For purposes of this section, the term: (a) "Defect" means: 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 1. Any failure, fault, or flaw in an electronic or electromechanical voting or other election system approved pursuant to s. 101.5605 which results in nonconformance with the standards in a manner that affects the timeliness or accuracy of the casting or counting of ballots; enables theft of, modification of, or access to confidential voter or election data; enables the introduction of malware; or exposes the state''s systems or data to bad actors outside the country or to individuals who are not United States citizens; or 2. Any failure or inability of the voting or other election system manufacturer or vendor to make available or provide approved replacements of hardware or software to the counties that have purchased the approved voting or other election system, the unavailability of which results in the system''s nonconformance with the standards in a manner that affects the timeliness or accuracy of the casting or counting of ballots or enables the insertion of illegal ballots, the change of or deletion of legal ballots, the fabrication of a false identity for voting purposes, or the impersonation of an eligible voter. (b) "Standards" refers to the requirements in ss. 101.5606 and 101.56062 under which a voting or other election system was approved for use in the state. (c) "Vendor" means a person who submits or previously submitted a voting or other election system that was approved by the Department of State in accordance with s. 101.5605, or a person who enters into a contract for the sale or lease of a voting or other election system to any county, or that previously entered into such a contract that has not expired. (2)(a) On January 1 of every odd-numbered year, each vendor shall file a written disclosure with the department identifying any known defect in the voting or other election system or the fact that there is no known defect, the effect of any defect on the operation and use of the approved voting system, and any known corrective measures to cure a defect, including, but not limited to, advisories and bulletins issued to system users. (b) Implementation of corrective measures approved by the department which enable a system to conform to the standards and ensure the timeliness and accuracy of the casting and counting of ballots constitutes a cure of a defect. (c) If a vendor becomes aware of the existence of a defect, he or she must file a new disclosure with the department as provided in paragraph (a) within 30 days after the date the vendor determined or reasonably should have determined that the defect existed. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (d) If a vendor discloses to the department that a defect exists, the department may suspend all sales or leases of the voting system in this the state and may suspend the use of the system in any election in this the state. If the department determines that the defect creates a security risk or impacts vote counting accuracy or the ballot acceptance error rate, the department must suspend the use of the system. The department shall provide written notice of any such suspension to each affected vendor and supervisor of elections. If the department determines that the defect no longer exists, the department must shall lift the suspension and provide written notice to each affected vendor and supervisor of elections. (e) If a vendor fails to file a required disclosure for a voting or other election system previously approved by the department, that system may not be sold, leased, or used for elections in this the state until it has been submitted for examination and approval and adopted for use pursuant to s. 101.5605. The department shall provide written notice to all supervisors of elections that the system is no longer approved. (3)(a) If the department has reasonable cause to believe a voting or other election system approved pursuant to s. 101.5605 contains a defect either before, during, or after an election which has not been disclosed pursuant to subsection (2), the department must may investigate whether the voting or other election system has a defect. (b) If the department has reasonable cause pursuant to paragraph (a) or if the supervisor of elections of a county that purchased or leased a voting or other election system that contains the alleged defect requests, in writing, an investigation by the department, the department must may initiate an investigation pursuant to paragraph (a) on its own initiative or upon the written request of the supervisor of elections of a county that purchased or leased a voting system that contains the alleged defect. (c) Upon initiating an investigation, the department shall provide written notice to the vendor and all of the supervisors of elections. (4)(a) If the department determines by a preponderance of the evidence that a defect exists in the voting system, or that a vendor failed to timely disclose a defect pursuant to subsection (2), the department must shall provide written notice to the affected vendor and supervisors of elections. (b) A vendor entitled to receive notice pursuant to paragraph (a) shall, within 10 days, file a written response to the department which: 1. Denies that the alleged defect exists or existed as alleged by the department or that the vendor failed to timely disclose a defect, and sets forth the reasons for such denial; or 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 2. Admits that the defect exists or existed as alleged by the department or that the vendor failed to timely disclose a defect. (c) If the defect has been cured, the vendor must shall provide an explanation of how the defect was cured. (d) If the defect has not been cured, the vendor must shall inform the department whether the defect can be cured and must shall provide the department with a plan for curing the defect. If the defect can be cured, the department must shall establish a timeframe within which to cure the defect. (5) If after receiving a response from the vendor, the department determines that a defect does not exist or has been cured within the timeframe established by the department, the department may not shall take no further action. (6) If the department determines that: a vendor failed to timely disclose a defect, ; or that a defect exists and a vendor has not filed a written response or has failed to cure within the timeframe established by the department, or if the defect cannot be cured, the department must shall impose a civil penalty of $25,000 for the defect plus an amount equal to the actual costs incurred by the department in conducting the investigation and the actual costs incurred by the supervisor of elections for any hand counts or recounts or for conducting a new election because of the defect. If the defect cannot be cured, the vendor must refund a prorated share of the purchase price based upon the remaining useful life of the system. (7)(a) If the department finds that a defect existed, : (a) the department may suspend all sales and leases of the voting or other election system and may suspend its use in any county in this the state. The department shall provide written notice of the suspension to each affected vendor and supervisor of elections. (b) If the department determines that a defect no longer exists in a voting or other election system that has been suspended from use pursuant to paragraph (a), the department must shall lift the suspension and authorize the sale, lease, and use of the voting or other election system in any election in this the state. The department shall provide written notice that the suspension has been lifted to each affected vendor and supervisor of elections. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (c) If the defect cannot be cured, the department may disapprove the voting or other election system for use in elections in the state. The department shall provide written notice to all supervisors of elections that the system is no longer approved. After approval of a system has been withdrawn pursuant to this paragraph, the system may not be sold, leased, or used in elections in the state until it has been submitted for examination and approval and adopted for use pursuant to s. 101.5605. (d) Any vendor against whom a civil penalty was imposed under this section may not submit a voting system for approval by the Department of State in accordance with s. 101.5605 or enter into a contract for sale or lease of a voting or other election system in this the state until the civil penalties have been paid and the department provides written confirmation to the supervisors of elections of the payment. (8) The department shall prepare a written report of any investigation conducted pursuant to this section. (9) The authority of the department under this section is in addition to, and not exclusive of, any other authority provided by law. (10) All proceedings under this section are exempt from chapter 120. Section 14. Section 101.5612, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 101.5612 Testing of voting and other election systems tabulating equipment. -- (1) Before installation, a certification team must inspect and approve all source code for tabulating and other election equipment. The Secretary of State and the department''s vendors shall maintain valid media-based extended validation certificates issued and recognized by certificate authorities to each entity in its own legal name. Each vendor shall prepare its source code package, prepare a digital signature using such certificate, and submit both to the secretary. The secretary shall publish, promptly and permanently, the submitted materials on his or her publicly available website for public access. The secretary shall perform his or her verification process. Upon successful verification, the secretary shall produce a digitally signed build of the software using the aforementioned certificate and permanently publish it on his or her publicly available website adjacent to the vendor''s source materials. This process must be followed for all subsequent change events, including modifications, enhancements, deletions, or replacements. Software may not be installed on any equipment that is not received from and signed by the secretary. A list of all systems, including the software version installed by the supervisors of elections, must be posted on the website and must be updated whenever the software versions are updated. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (2) All electronic or electromechanical voting systems must shall be thoroughly tested at the conclusion of maintenance and programming. Tests must shall be sufficient to determine all of the following: that (a) Whether the voting system is properly programmed. , (b) Whether the election is correctly defined on the voting system. , and (c) Whether all of the voting system input, output, and communication devices are working properly. (d) Whether all settings are per department and security plan guidelines. (e) Whether all security and system software is up to date. (f) Whether any unauthorized software has been installed. (g) Whether the system is free from malware. (h) Whether all removable storage is secure. (i) That unauthorized communications capability has not been installed. (j) Whether all of the input, output, and communication devices are working properly. The same testing standards, including verification that the specified functions are working properly, must be implemented on other election systems. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (3) (2) On any day not more than 25 days before the commencement of early voting as provided in s. 101.657, the supervisor of elections shall have the automatic tabulating equipment and other election equipment publicly tested. The equipment testing must to ascertain that the equipment will correctly count the votes cast for all offices and on all measures. If the ballots to be used at the polling place on election day are not available at the time of the testing, the supervisor must may conduct an additional test not more than 10 days before election day. Other election system testing must ascertain that the system will correctly perform its designated functions during the election, such as having the automated signature verification systems tested to determine whether they properly perform signature verification and are properly calibrated. Public notice of the time and place of the testing of voting and other election equipment must test shall be given at least 48 hours prior thereto by publication on the county website as provided in s. 50.0311, on the supervisor of elections'' website, or once in one or more newspapers of general circulation in the county. If the applicable website becomes unavailable or if there is no newspaper of general circulation in the county, the notice must be posted in at least four conspicuous places in the county. The supervisor or the municipal elections official shall may, at the time of qualifying, give written notice of the time and location of the public preelection test to each candidate qualifying with that office and obtain a signed receipt that the notice has been given. The Department of State shall give written notice to each statewide candidate at the time of qualifying, or immediately at the end of qualifying, that the voting equipment will be tested and advise each candidate to contact the county supervisor of elections as to the time and location of the public preelection test. The supervisor or the municipal elections official shall, at least 30 days before the commencement of early voting as provided in s. 101.657, send written notice by certified mail to the county party chair of each political party and to all candidates for other than statewide office whose names appear on the ballot in the county and who did not receive written notification from the supervisor or municipal elections official at the time of qualifying, stating the time and location of the public preelection test of the automatic tabulating equipment and other election systems. The canvassing board shall convene, and each member of the canvassing board shall certify to the accuracy of the test. For the test, the canvassing board may designate one member to represent it. The test must shall be open to representatives of the political parties, the press, and the public. Each political party may designate one person with expertise in the computer field who shall be allowed in the central counting room or work area when all tests are being conducted and when the official votes are being counted. The party designee may observe the other election systems during election operations, may request inspection of and photograph the system settings, may receive and retain these settings in print form, and may have access to a hotline to report technology issues. The public must be allowed to observe all tabulating equipment and election equipment while in use, either through direct observation or a video stream, and to request inspection of system settings provided that voter privacy is maintained. The designee or the public may not interfere with the normal operation of the canvassing board or election operations. However, the designee and the public must be able to call a hotline when an issue is 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 identified and submit a work ticket. The calls to the hotline must be monitored by the state and the canvassing board. A political party may select to have the designees of the party monitor the hotline. (4) (3) For electronic or electromechanical voting systems configured to tabulate vote-by-mail ballots at a central or regional site, the public testing must shall be conducted by processing a preaudited group of ballots so produced as to record a predetermined number of valid votes for each candidate and on each measure and to include one or more ballots for each office which have activated voting positions in excess of the number allowed by law in order to test the ability of the automatic tabulating equipment to reject such votes. If any error is detected, the cause therefor must shall be corrected and an errorless count must shall be made before the automatic tabulating equipment is approved. The test must shall be repeated and errorless results achieved immediately before the start of the official count of the ballots and again after the completion of the official count. The programs and ballots used for testing must shall be sealed and retained under the custody of the county canvassing board. Immediately after the preaudited group of ballots is run and results reconciled, a randomly selected number of test ballots from one or more public participants must be chosen. After the batch of ballots provided by the public is reconciled, the two batches must be comingled and reconciled again. The test of combined public and preaudited ballots must also be repeated and errorless results achieved immediately before the start of the official count of the ballots and again after the completion of the official count. (5)(a)1. (4)(a)1. For electronic or electromechanical voting systems configured to include electronic or electromechanical tabulation devices which are distributed to the precincts or used in an absentee vote counting center, all or a sample of the devices to be used in the election must shall be publicly tested. If a sample is to be tested, the sample shall consist of a random selection of at least 5 percent or 10 of the devices for an optical scan system, whichever is greater. For touchscreen systems used for voters having a disability, all a sample of at least 2 percent of the devices must be tested. The test must shall be conducted by processing a group of no fewer than 20 ballots, causing the device to output results for the ballots processed, and comparing the output of results to the results expected for the ballots processed. The group of ballots must shall be produced so as to record a predetermined number of valid votes for each candidate and on each measure and to include for each office one or more ballots which have activated voting positions in excess of the number allowed by law in order to test the ability of the tabulating device to reject such votes. Immediately after the official group of test ballots is run and results reconciled, a batch of up to 20 random test ballots from one or more public participants must be chosen if there are more than 20 ballot submissions proposed. After the batch of ballots provided by the public is reconciled, the two batches must be comingled and reconciled again. The test of combined public and official test ballots must be repeated and errorless results achieved immediately before the start of the official count of the ballots and again after the completion of the official count. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 2. If any tested tabulating device is found to have an error in tabulation or other election system is determined to have an error in its function or security measures, it must shall be deemed unsatisfactory. For each device deemed unsatisfactory, a report on the finding must be written and be publicly available for review. For each device or system deemed unsatisfactory, the canvassing board shall, with assistance from a county or state information technology expert, shall take steps to determine the cause of the error, shall attempt to identify and test other devices that could reasonably be expected to have the same error, and shall test a number of additional devices sufficient to determine that all devices are satisfactory. Upon deeming any device unsatisfactory, the canvassing board may require all devices to be tested or may declare that all devices are unsatisfactory. The system may not allow remote logins. 3. If the operation or output of any tested tabulation device, such as spelling or the order of candidates on a report, is in error, such problem must shall be reported to the canvassing board. The canvassing board shall then determine whether if the reported problem warrants its deeming the device unsatisfactory. (b) At the completion of testing under this subsection, the canvassing board or its representative, the representatives of the political parties, and the candidates or their representatives who attended the test shall witness the resetting of each device that passed to a preelection state of readiness, and the sealing of its USB ports and other physical ports through which malware may be inserted, and the verification of its power receptacle using tamper evident uniquely serialized official security seals. Once sealed, the device or system must have a removable sticker placed on it which can be seen by public observers and employees. Such sticker must have a device or system identifier and checkboxes for each test performed and passed, including settings. The list of validated settings must be posted next to the test sticker each device that passed in such a manner as to secure its state of readiness until the opening of the polls. (c) The canvassing board or its representative shall execute a written statement setting forth the tabulation devices and other election systems tested, the results of the testing, the protective counter numbers, if applicable, of each tabulation device, the number of the seals seal securing each tabulation device or other election system at the conclusion of testing, any problems reported to the board as a result of the testing, and whether each device tested is satisfactory or unsatisfactory. (d) Any tabulating device or other election system deemed unsatisfactory must shall be recoded, repaired, or replaced and must shall be made available for retesting. Such device must be determined by the canvassing board or its representative to be satisfactory before it may be used in any election. The canvassing board or its representative shall announce at the close of the first testing the date, place, and time that any unsatisfactory device will be retested or may, at the option of the board, notify by telephone each person who was present at the first testing as to the date, place, and time that the retesting will occur. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (e) Records must be kept of all preelection testing of electronic or electromechanical tabulation devices and other election systems used in any election. Such records are to be present and available for inspection and reference during public preelection testing by any person in attendance during such testing and through a public records request at no charge. The test records may also be posted on the election office website. The need of the canvassing board for access to such records during the testing takes shall take precedence over the need of other attendees or the public to access such records so that the work of the canvassing board will not be delayed or hindered. Records of testing must include, for each device, the name of each person who tested the device and the date, place, time, and results of each test. Records of testing must shall be retained as part of the official records of the election in which any device was used for a period of 22 months after election certification. (6) (5) Any tests involving marksense ballots pursuant to this section must shall employ test ballots created by the supervisor of elections using actual ballots that have been printed for the election. If ballot-on-demand ballots will be used in the election, the supervisor must shall also create test ballots using the ballot-on-demand technology that will be used to produce ballots in the election, using the same paper stock as will be used for ballots in the election. Section 15. Section 101.591, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 101.591 Voting and other election system audit. -- (1) On the second day after the closing of the polls Immediately following the certification of each election, the county canvassing board or the local board responsible for certifying the election shall conduct a manual audit and may also conduct or an automated, independent audit of the voting systems used in randomly selected precincts. The manual audit must be conducted in at least one precinct for each race on the ballot, and the precinct in which the race is audited must be randomly selected. The number of precincts where a manual audit is conducted must be no less than 5 percent but no more than 10 percent of the precincts. If this results in more precincts than races, the additional precincts must have a randomly selected race audited. If 5 percent of the precincts yields fewer than 5 precincts, the county canvassing board or the local board responsible for certifying the election must randomly chose at least 5 precincts. Random precincts must be selected using a lottery at a publicly noticed canvassing board meeting. If the results of the manual audit show a discrepancy of more than the margin of victory in any race, that race may not be certified until the discrepancy is resolved. If such discrepancy cannot be resolved, there must be a manual recount of the race in all precincts. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (2)(a) For each precinct and race selected, a manual audit must shall consist of a public manual tally of the votes cast using original paper ballots in one randomly selected race that appears on the ballot. The tally sheet for the precinct must shall include election-day, vote-by-mail, early voting, provisional, and overseas ballots collected and counted through election day. The canvassing board and public observers must be present for the retrieval of sealed ballots, the opening of seals, and the manual recount. The manual recount procedure must be videotaped and livestreamed , in at least 1 percent but no more than 2 percent of the precincts chosen at random by the county canvassing board or the local board responsible for certifying the election. If 1 percent of the precincts is less than one entire precinct, the audit shall be conducted using at least one precinct chosen at random by the county canvassing board or the local board responsible for certifying the election. Such precincts shall be selected at a publicly noticed canvassing board meeting. (b) An automated audit must shall consist of a public automated tally of the votes cast across every race that appears on the ballot and must use the original paper ballots. The tally sheet must shall include election day, vote-by-mail, early voting, provisional, and overseas ballots in at least 20 percent of the precincts chosen at random by the county canvassing board or the local board responsible for certifying the election. Such precincts must shall be randomly selected at a publicly noticed canvassing board meeting. (c) The division shall adopt rules for approval of an independent audit system which provide that the system, at a minimum, must be: 1. Completely independent of the primary voting system. 2. Fast enough to produce final audit results within the timeframe prescribed in subsection (4). 3. Capable of demonstrating that the ballots of record have been accurately adjudicated by the audit system. (3) The canvassing board shall post a notice of the audit, including the date, time, and place, in four conspicuous places in the county and on the home page of the county supervisor of elections website. (4) The audit must be completed and the results made public before no later than 11:59 p.m. on the 7th day following certification of the election by the county canvassing board or the local board responsible for certifying the election. 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (5) By December 15 of each general election year, the county canvassing board or the board responsible for certifying the election shall provide a report with the results of the audit to the Department of State in a standard format as prescribed by the department. The report must be consolidated into one report with the overvote and undervote report required under s. 101.595(1). The report must shall contain, but is not limited to, the following items: (a) The overall accuracy of audit. (b) A description of any problems or discrepancies encountered. (c) The likely cause of such problems or discrepancies. (d) Recommended corrective action with respect to avoiding or mitigating such circumstances in future elections. (6) If a manual recount is undertaken pursuant to s. 102.166, the canvassing board is not required to perform the audit provided for in this section. Section 16. Paragraph (a) of subsection (2) of section 101.68, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 101.68 Canvassing of vote-by-mail ballot. -- (2)(a) The county canvassing board may begin the canvassing of vote-by-mail ballots upon the completion of the public testing of automatic tabulating equipment pursuant to s. 101.5612(3) s. 101.5612(2), but must begin such canvassing by no later than noon on the day following the election. However, notwithstanding any such authorization to begin canvassing or otherwise processing vote- by-mail ballots early, no result shall be released until after the closing of the polls in that county on election day. Any supervisor, deputy supervisor, canvassing board member, election board member, or election employee who releases the results of a canvassing or processing of vote-by mail ballots prior to the closing of the polls in that county on election day commits a felony of the third degree, punishable as provided in s. 775.082, s. 775.083, or s. 775.084. Section 17. Paragraph (c) of subsection (2) of section 101.69, Florida Statutes, is amended to read: 101.69 Voting in person; return of vote-by-mail ballot. -- (2) 3/10/26, 5:30 PM State Net | Bill | (2025) FL S 394 (c)1. On each day of early voting, all secure ballot intake stations must be emptied at the end of early voting hours and all ballots retrieved from the secure ballot intake stations must be returned to the supervisor''s office. 2. For secure ballot intake stations located at an office of the supervisor, all ballots must be retrieved before the secure ballot intake station is no longer monitored by an employee of the supervisor. 3. Employees of the supervisor must comply with procedures for the chain of custody of ballots as required by s. 101.015(6) s. 101.015(4). Section 18. This act shall take effect July 1, 2025. Copyright © 2026 State Net. All Rights Reserved.'
);

